## Measurements

### Temperature and Flow Rate Data

<div style="overflow-x:auto;">

| Run | Configuration      | Tc,in (°C) | Th,in (°C) | Tc,out (°C) | Th,out (°C) | Flow Rate (gal/hr) |
|-----|-------------------|------------|------------|-------------|-------------|--------------------|
| 1   | Parallel flow     | 6.8        | 40.0       | 15.9        | 24.6        | 210                |
| 2   | Parallel flow     | 8.7        | 35.0       | 21.1        | 23.7        | 210                |
| 3   | Counterflow       | 9.2        | 35.0       | 22.1        | 18.0        | 210                |
| 4   | Counterflow (hot) | 10.0       | 40.0       | 23.9        | 19.6        | 210                |

</div>

![Measured temperatures](/assets/images/image-2.png)

---

### Heat Transfer Results

<div style="overflow-x:auto;">

| Run | Configuration      | ΔTc (K) | Qc (kW) | ΔTh (K) | Qh (kW) |
|-----|-------------------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
| 1   | Parallel flow     | 9.1     | 8.40    | 15.4    | 14.21   |
| 2   | Parallel flow     | 12.4    | 11.44   | 11.3    | 10.43   |
| 3   | Counterflow       | 12.9    | 11.91   | 17.0    | 15.69   |
| 4   | Counterflow (hot) | 13.9    | 12.83   | 20.4    | 18.83   |

</div>

Based on cold-side measurements, the heat exchanger transferred approximately **8–13 kW** across all runs.

Differences between Qc and Qh are expected due to real-system effects, including heat loss to the surroundings, unequal pump flow rates, imperfect reservoir mixing, and sensor lag or placement. These deviations are typical for experimental systems and differ from idealized textbook models.

---

### Effectiveness

![Effectiveness comparison](/assets/images/image-3.png)

<div style="overflow-x:auto;">

| Run | Configuration      | Effectiveness (ε) |
|-----|-------------------|------------------|
| 1   | Parallel flow     | 0.27             |
| 2   | Parallel flow     | 0.47             |
| 3   | Counterflow       | 0.50             |
| 4   | Counterflow (hot) | 0.46             |

</div>

For the most direct comparison between flow arrangements, Run 2 (parallel flow) and Run 3 (counterflow) were analyzed because they had nearly identical hot-side inlet temperatures (approximately 35 °C) and similar cold-side inlet conditions. Under these matched conditions, the counterflow configuration demonstrated slightly higher effectiveness and greater heat transfer to the cold stream.

---

## Conclusions

This experiment demonstrated a realistic thermodynamic analysis of a working heat exchanger:

- Cold-side heat transfer rates ranged from approximately **8 to 13 kW**  
- Under similar inlet conditions, **counterflow achieved higher effectiveness** (0.50) than parallel flow (0.47)  
- Increasing the hot-reservoir inlet temperature in counterflow increased heat transfer by approximately **8%**  
- Energy-rate mismatches between hot and cold sides were expected due to real heat losses and flow nonuniformities  

Overall, this lab provided a concrete example of applying mass, energy, and entropy balances to a real engineering device and illustrated how both design choices (flow arrangement) and operating conditions (inlet temperature) directly affect heat exchanger performance.
